WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.800
So, thank you for coming to this presentation.

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:14.040
My name is Mike K. Smith, I lead up the R Center of Excellence in the SWAT team.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:26.799
And on the 3rd of October this year, 2023, I'll be celebrating 30 years employed at Pfizer.

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:32.360
And in the talk today, what I want to try and talk to you about is the fact that right

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.160
now in industry, things are changing.

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:41.400
Things are changing fast because the industry is looking at R and other open source tools

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:46.480
more and more for clinical trial reporting and for regulatory submissions.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:51.980
So I want to look at that in the context of what was it like 30 years ago, how far have

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:56.020
we come, and also a little bit of crystal ball gazing about what the future might be

00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:58.139
like.

00:00:58.139 --> 00:01:09.739
So let's jump in the DeLorean, set the destination for 1993, October, and go back and see what

00:01:09.739 --> 00:01:10.940
things are like.

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:17.580
I will be your Doc Emmett Brown guide to this, but when we get back there we might meet this

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:20.059
young lad, right?

00:01:20.059 --> 00:01:23.199
So please, if you find him, be gentle.

00:01:23.199 --> 00:01:25.739
This is his first week in industry.

00:01:25.739 --> 00:01:26.739
This is his first job.

00:01:26.739 --> 00:01:31.739
He's moved 500 miles from home to come and work for Pfizer down in East Kent.

00:01:31.739 --> 00:01:36.940
He's also slightly bewildered because he's started into this industry where people know

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:40.500
how to do clever things with SAS, and he's never used SAS before, so he's going to have

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:42.459
to learn.

00:01:42.459 --> 00:01:45.959
Now, think back 30 years.

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:52.839
So if you are less than, oh, I would say 40, the thing on the far left is not just the

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:59.720
save icon, but it's an actual data storage device that holds a whopping 1.4 megabytes

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:03.599
of information, megabytes.

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:06.519
But obviously, over time, things have changed.

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:07.879
Technology has moved on.

00:02:07.879 --> 00:02:14.179
We've gone through CD-ROMs, DVDs, and right now you can essentially download almost an

00:02:14.179 --> 00:02:17.820
arbitrary amount of information from the internet and from the cloud.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:20.300
So 30 years ago, what's a cloud?

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:23.539
Well, cloud computing isn't just something that happens in the west of Scotland where

00:02:23.539 --> 00:02:27.179
it rains a lot, right?

00:02:27.179 --> 00:02:33.699
But 30 years ago, the industry really was predominantly SAS-based, right?

00:02:33.699 --> 00:02:38.820
SAS was the lingua franca for all the work that was done for clinical trial reporting,

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:44.100
and I would say 90%, 95% of the work was done in SAS.

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:51.860
Back in 1993, a full-stack developer used one tool, this one, but what they did was

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:57.899
data manipulation, analysis, programming of tables, listings, and figures, right?

00:02:57.899 --> 00:02:59.179
So that was your full stack.

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:03.699
You did end-to-end work, but all of it in SAS.

00:03:03.699 --> 00:03:11.220
The other thing that happened in 93, or very shortly before 93, was that R became a thing.

00:03:11.339 --> 00:03:18.339
Now, back in 93, R was more of an academic statistical software for statisticians to

00:03:18.339 --> 00:03:21.059
fit models and do interesting things like that.

00:03:21.059 --> 00:03:28.179
It certainly wasn't the programming language that we know about today.

00:03:28.179 --> 00:03:31.179
Let me talk also about regulatory submissions.

00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:36.539
So at the end of the clinical trial development process, we have to gather together all of

00:03:36.539 --> 00:03:43.179
the information that we have on our therapeutic or our treatment, bundle it all together,

00:03:43.179 --> 00:03:48.779
and back in 93, that involved printing it out, binding it, putting those binders together

00:03:48.779 --> 00:03:54.740
onto a pallet, shrink-wrapping it, and literally trucking it to the regulatory agency.

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:55.899
This is how we did it.

00:03:55.899 --> 00:03:59.979
So that's an example regulatory submission, and you can see what kind of amount of volume

00:03:59.979 --> 00:04:02.539
of information is in there.

00:04:02.539 --> 00:04:09.940
Fast forward a little bit, 30 years on, we're still producing largely the same static information,

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:12.380
but it's now in electronic format.

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:17.500
And there's an electronic submission to the regulatory agencies.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:24.660
But still, we've come a long way, but it's maybe to someone 30 years ago, what they would

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:28.859
see in this electronic submission would be very familiar.

00:04:28.859 --> 00:04:37.940
So that says to me that there's a well-founded perception that pharma is very slow to change.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:41.779
And I would also argue that there's, across all of the pharma companies, there's a certain

00:04:41.779 --> 00:04:48.220
amount of hubris that says, well, if this isn't developed by me within my company, I'm

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:53.059
not sure that the quality is really up to Pfizer standards.

00:04:53.059 --> 00:04:59.459
And that, I think, prevents us from engaging with the open source community and bringing

00:04:59.459 --> 00:05:05.660
in outside work to help us with our jobs.

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:10.220
But let me tell you right now, change is happening.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:11.779
Pay attention to the tense there.

00:05:11.779 --> 00:05:14.779
It is happening.

00:05:14.779 --> 00:05:16.059
It's not coming.

00:05:16.059 --> 00:05:18.260
It's here now.

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:23.540
Last week, we heard from Novo Nordisk that they had completed and filed an NDA, a new

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:29.540
drug application to the FDA, predominantly using R. So using R and SASP, but in the whole

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:33.700
tables, listings, and figures and data manipulation, used R.

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:39.019
This is the single biggest question I get from anyone that says, yes, using R for clinical

00:05:39.019 --> 00:05:40.380
trial reporting is a nice idea.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:42.940
But has anyone actually done it in practice?

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:46.980
And the answer now is, yes, yes, they have.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.660
If you haven't seen that video, I encourage you to go and have a look.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:54.940
It's really a great eye-opener because Novo are talking in very kind of candid ways about

00:05:54.940 --> 00:05:57.140
what they've done and how they've done it.

00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:59.899
The other thing is that the change is accelerating.

00:05:59.899 --> 00:06:02.700
The pace of change is accelerating.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:07.619
And if you're sitting at the sidelines looking in and going, yep, this looks interesting,

00:06:07.619 --> 00:06:12.859
but I'll give it a little while and see how other people get on with it, you might find

00:06:12.859 --> 00:06:18.380
yourself far further back in the change curve.

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:19.980
So what does this change look like?

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:25.540
Well, there's a collection of R packages called the Pharmaverse that helps the industry with

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:29.420
all aspects of preparing for this regulatory submission.

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:35.980
So data manipulation, tables, listings, and figures, and presentation of those tables,

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:42.700
listings, and figures, as well as things like infrastructure bits or environment management,

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:46.579
also validating R packages and testing R packages.

00:06:46.579 --> 00:06:50.220
So there's a huge amount of work done in here.

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:54.700
The other great thing is this is work done across a huge number of different companies.

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:59.299
And as you can see here, a significant number of people.

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:05.839
So this is all great information that you can tap into and exploit and see how much

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:09.380
of it is useful to you for your process today.

00:07:09.380 --> 00:07:12.220
But it's not just R packages that people are developing.

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:15.299
People are developing training modules.

00:07:15.299 --> 00:07:21.500
So this is a great example where Genentech have made their training course on open source

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:27.260
development and using GitHub to develop new things and how to work in that framework,

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:31.179
and then made it available to any of us in this room to go and evaluate this course and

00:07:31.179 --> 00:07:33.100
see how it works.

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:37.380
And that's fantastic, because it brings all of our skill levels up.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:42.980
So when we ask, how do we do this, we can all now work off that same level playing field

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:44.380
of knowledge.

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:47.859
And that, I think, is quite extraordinary.

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:50.820
A lot of these initiatives are powered by consortium.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:56.739
So there are three listed here, FUSE, R Consortium, and Open Source Informer.

00:07:56.739 --> 00:08:01.619
And what these consortia do is that they give a platform for multiple different companies

00:08:01.619 --> 00:08:04.140
to come together and discuss freely.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:05.380
But not just companies.

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:08.420
It's also the regulatory agencies.

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:14.779
In this R Submissions working group from R Consortium, the FDA are active members and

00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:21.420
engaged, and they are defining how they want things to be, because they want to shape what

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:24.179
that next generation reporting looks like.

00:08:24.179 --> 00:08:26.899
And I think that's really powerful.

00:08:26.899 --> 00:08:32.419
Rather than it being powered by pharma companies who want to do something fancy, the regulators

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:35.619
themselves are sitting at the table and going, well, we have a stake in this.

00:08:35.619 --> 00:08:39.700
We want to tell you, we want to shape what you're going to do with this.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:45.059
But these three organizations are driving that change in a way that, you know, I've

00:08:45.059 --> 00:08:48.539
never seen anything like this in the last three years, last 30 years.

00:08:48.539 --> 00:08:53.580
I would say that in the last five years, the pace has picked up enormously.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:56.940
Even in the last two years, it's accelerated again.

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:02.140
So these consortia really are powering that change.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:08.020
You might say to yourself, why would companies share this knowledge?

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:09.580
Isn't that our intellectual property?

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:16.099
And 30 years ago, yes, if I wanted to talk to someone in Roche about how Pfizer do things,

00:09:16.099 --> 00:09:19.580
our internal legal people would get rather twitchy.

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:23.640
But if we do it through consortia now in a working group, that gives us this level playing

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:27.539
field that says anyone can come and talk at this within this working group.

00:09:27.539 --> 00:09:31.940
And it frees us to be open and candid about how we're doing things and try to find the

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:32.979
best way.

00:09:32.979 --> 00:09:36.219
Because it's not just Pfizer want to find the best way.

00:09:36.219 --> 00:09:40.299
We want to find the best way and hear what Roche are doing and Genentech are doing and

00:09:40.299 --> 00:09:45.700
all these other companies, and then help that inform how we move forward.

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:50.460
So the IP now is people are saying, well, I think the IP is in the treatments we develop

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:53.260
and then the data that we collect.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:55.859
Not in how I code that visualization.

00:09:55.859 --> 00:09:59.340
And I think that's eminently sensible.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:02.859
So let's have a wee bit of a guess about what the future might bring.

00:10:02.859 --> 00:10:09.940
Please, believe me, I am not telling you that in 30 years we'll have hoverboards because

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:12.539
by now we should have had them, right?

00:10:12.539 --> 00:10:14.179
So it's always dangerous.

00:10:14.179 --> 00:10:18.619
Neil Sparrow, the physicist, says prediction is difficult, particularly where the future

00:10:18.619 --> 00:10:19.619
is concerned.

00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:21.140
So bear that in mind.

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:27.700
But what I want to talk about now is some of the things I see and the kind of directions

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:29.900
that I think are going to be important.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:37.020
So we all will, if you don't know about Quarto, you will at the end of this conference.

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:41.099
But the principle behind Quarto is reproducible reporting.

00:10:41.099 --> 00:10:47.219
And I think that's going to be really important to be able to demonstrate that this table

00:10:47.219 --> 00:10:51.219
listing figure that I'm producing can be done again and again and again.

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:55.940
And if I feed that same data through, I'll predictably get the same answer.

00:10:55.940 --> 00:11:01.200
In the middle, I'm talking about WebR, but really what I'm meaning here is the regulators

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:07.219
want to have a little bit more dynamic review of what we're presenting, as opposed to those

00:11:07.219 --> 00:11:10.739
static images and listings and tables.

00:11:10.739 --> 00:11:17.460
WebR is a good example because you can bake that interactivity into a single HTML document,

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:23.179
and that's easy to send to an agency, where sending a Shiny app depends on a server, which

00:11:23.179 --> 00:11:26.539
depends on infrastructure, which depends on package versions and a whole bundle of

00:11:26.539 --> 00:11:29.859
other things that get a bit squarely and difficult.

00:11:29.859 --> 00:11:35.539
Lastly, on the right-hand side, the theme I'm talking about here is interactive graphics.

00:11:35.539 --> 00:11:37.739
So the fact that it's eCharts, you know, pick your own.

00:11:37.739 --> 00:11:43.380
It could be observable, it could be Rd4 or anything else.

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:50.179
But the point is, we are all looking for that little bit more interactivity in our visualizations

00:11:50.380 --> 00:11:55.419
so that we can drill down into something and go, what subjects are involved in this data

00:11:55.419 --> 00:11:56.419
point?

00:11:56.419 --> 00:12:04.619
Or who is this person here, and can I see what other endpoints pertain to that individual?

00:12:04.619 --> 00:12:07.419
The other thing is that data is all around us now.

00:12:07.419 --> 00:12:13.359
30 years ago, if you wanted to know how a patient felt about a treatment and their daily

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:18.580
snapshot of their endpoints, you gave them a paper diary, which they filled in every

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:21.380
day, they brought back and we digitized it.

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:26.460
Or you gave them a meeting with their clinician at the end of treatment, and they would ask

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:27.460
questions.

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:34.260
But today, with wearables, apps, all of these things, we can get a much richer view, a daily

00:12:34.260 --> 00:12:38.099
view, an hour-by-hour view of the patient's experience.

00:12:38.099 --> 00:12:42.140
So for example, you could have a wearable that measures tremor and shake in a Parkinson's

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:46.059
patient, continuously.

00:12:46.059 --> 00:12:50.619
Which I think it makes the analysis a lot more complicated, but it gives a much richer

00:12:50.619 --> 00:12:56.200
and more nuanced view of exactly what's happening for that patient.

00:12:56.200 --> 00:13:01.179
Another thing is that patients are having a much greater say in what the industry does

00:13:01.179 --> 00:13:03.599
with their data.

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:09.659
So they may give consent for their data to be used in its primary use of clinical trial

00:13:09.659 --> 00:13:15.460
reporting and for the submission to the regulator agencies, they may opt out of secondary use

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:22.020
of that data for things like building ML models or AI models, and we have to respect that.

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:26.820
Patient advocacy groups are now much more data literate than they were 30 years ago.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:31.700
They're used to seeing data, they have people in those advocacy groups who can analyze that

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:38.280
data, interpret it, understand it, and then make a case for what they would like to happen.

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:44.500
And lastly, patients have the right for their data to be forgotten.

00:13:44.539 --> 00:13:48.619
So a patient could come back and say, I don't want my data in your database anymore, and

00:13:48.619 --> 00:13:51.419
we have to respect that, honor it, and expunge it.

00:13:51.419 --> 00:13:57.820
Now again, 30 years ago, that would have been a really big ask, but these kinds of things

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:02.119
are, we now need to manage for those things.

00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:07.140
So all of this change means that we need to build trust.

00:14:07.140 --> 00:14:11.219
We need to build trust between the developers of these packages, who are across all of these

00:14:11.219 --> 00:14:12.380
different organizations.

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:17.539
We need to build trust that if I pick up your package and use it for my purposes, I

00:14:17.539 --> 00:14:22.380
trust that you're doing a good job, that you've thought of all the edge cases, or you've tested

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:24.580
it adequately.

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:31.380
There's trust between the industry and the regulatory agencies, and that trust is built

00:14:31.380 --> 00:14:37.780
largely through those consortia working groups, because we're talking about it monthly when

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:39.260
we get together.

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:43.500
And obviously, it depends on trust between the patients and the pharma industry to make

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:49.820
sure that we are treating their data with respect.

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:55.979
Let me give you a little cautionary tale about predicting future technology.

00:14:55.979 --> 00:15:00.140
The books that you see here are what's called an encyclopedia.

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:06.020
You used to find them in buildings that were called libraries, and it's a printed volume,

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:10.700
and they had hundreds of articles about all kinds of topics, and if you wanted to know

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:15.460
about that specific topic, you'd go to the library, you'd extract the volume, you'd look

00:15:15.460 --> 00:15:18.179
it up, and you'd find out your information.

00:15:18.179 --> 00:15:26.140
Those things went out of date really quickly, but guaranteed you'd find a set in a library.

00:15:26.140 --> 00:15:32.000
And then Microsoft said, well, with the advent of the CD-ROM and the DVD, we can now go from

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.679
hundreds of articles about information to thousands, tens of thousands of articles,

00:15:36.679 --> 00:15:41.559
and we can have embedded media clips so that people can see and get more information about

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:42.559
this.

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:46.960
And, you know, largely because information goes out of date very quickly, obviously,

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:50.559
they could sell annual updates to this product.

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:51.840
That's a great idea, right?

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:56.200
That's revolutionary, until something like this happens.

00:15:56.200 --> 00:16:04.080
And now you've got an open, community-curated encyclopedia with millions of articles, tens

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:08.440
of millions of articles, edited by all of us.

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:13.880
If we have a deep knowledge of a certain sitcom, we can go in and we can contribute to an article

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:14.880
on it.

00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:16.239
And that's amazing, right?

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:17.440
It's revolutionary.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:21.880
And the other thing is it's available in any browser, on any device, on your phone, on

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:25.239
your tablet, on your computer, everywhere you go.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:30.119
If you're at a trivia night and you have a debate with your colleague about who was it

00:16:30.119 --> 00:16:34.479
in that film that did that thing, you can now look it up.

00:16:34.479 --> 00:16:41.200
Thirty years ago, this kind of community-led thing would have been astounding, right?

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:42.200
Still is quite astounding.

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:45.400
But 30 years ago, you would have been laughed out of town.

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:47.679
So believe me that change is here.

00:16:47.679 --> 00:16:48.679
It's coming.

00:16:48.679 --> 00:16:49.719
It's accelerating.

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:55.119
And like the Wikipedia, don't let yourself be the Microsoft and Carta team.

00:16:55.119 --> 00:16:59.640
Sitting there trying to sell a product that is just about to be trumped by an open source

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:05.640
thing that will blow you out of the water and change your world, okay?

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:09.239
So with that, I must say I'm out of time.

00:17:09.239 --> 00:17:14.560
But like Natalia, here's my QR code for all kinds of links to the things I've talked about

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:15.719
and how to connect to me.

00:17:15.719 --> 00:17:16.719
So thanks very much.

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:26.160
Thank you, Mike.

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:29.599
So we wait for some questions here.

00:17:29.599 --> 00:17:33.599
What is the thing that excites you the most right now that you're looking forward to happening

00:17:33.599 --> 00:17:36.160
as you're seeing all this sea of changes?

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:41.079
I'm really excited about moving away from static outputs.

00:17:41.079 --> 00:17:50.160
So the idea that you can have nice, clear, informative visuals, which are also rich.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:51.599
So you can delve into them.

00:17:51.599 --> 00:17:54.880
You can see different layers of information.

